column3: or have been diagnosed with life-threatening illnesses. We encourage and inspire this special population of children to reach for the highest possible goals – intellectually
column4: socially and physically.

column1: The Foundation operates Frankie’s World
column2: a Prescribed Pediatric Extended Care Center or PPECC
column3: licensed by the State of Pennsylvania. It opened on July 19
column5: and is centrally located in Northern Liberties to be accessible to children from all parts of Philadelphia. When my daughter Frankie was a toddler on a ventilator in 2000
column6: she was isolated at home with a nurse
column7: and there was no medically-safe place for her to go to make friends and learn about the world. We made Frankie’s World into the kind of place she would have loved.

column1: Our state-of-the-art facility is staffed by experienced pediatric nurses and special needs educators. The interior is a large open playroom
column2: equipped with toys
column3: books
column4: games
column10: and much more – every item carefully selected to maximize a child's opportunity for physical
column12: and intellectual growth and development. Nursing services include tracheotomy/ventilator care
column14: medication administration
column15: and seizure monitoring. There is no cost to parents – we will work with your child's doctor and insurance company.

column1: Frankie's World is a safe and loving environment where children can play
column2: learn and thrive while their parents are away at work or school. column2: APM responded to the overwhelming need to provide affordable childcare services within its community by opening the first of two early childhood education centers in North Philadelphia.  Our programs are NAECY-certified and have achieved a Keystone 4-STAR rating.

column1: The goal of our early childhood education programs is to promote the cultural
column2: cognitive
column3: social
column4: emotional and physical development of young children.  Each child has the opportunity to experience programs that feature age-appropriate developmental learning and enrichment activities
column5: ensuring that children reach their fullest potential while in our care.  We place a strong emphasis on parent involvement and on positive reinforcement
column6: thereby building children's self esteem in a safe and caring environment.  Our staff is highly capable and works successfully with children diagnosed with developmental disabilities.

column1: At APM
column2: each classroom is led by experienced bilingual (English/Spanish) and bicultural teachers and assistants with formal training.  We require that all staff participate in continuous training opportunities
column3: ensuring that the latest child development research tools are applied in our curriculum. 713616;"GRACE DAY CARE CENTER( GRACE UNITED METHODIST CHUR";"7101 N 20TH ST";"PHILADELPHIA";"PA";19138;"PHILADELPHIA";2155490619;"http://www.unitedmethodisthomes.org/about-us/history/";;"In the mid-1940s
column2: the Reverend Harry Brooks began a campaign to start a “Homes for the Aging” program out of his deep concern for the welfare of the elderly members of the Wyoming Conference of United Methodist congregations. On September 28
column4: the Methodist Homes for the Aged was incorporated in the State of Pennsylvania.

column1: Building on this work
column2: the Reverend Dr. Russell Hawke
column3: Superintendent of the Scranton District of the Wyoming Conference
column4: helped establish a small home for the elderly that would accommodate 20 to 25 residents
column5: planned to be the first of many. As funds became available
column6: the Methodist Homes for the Aging of the Wyoming Conference in the State of New York was incorporated in 1958
column7: for the purpose of expanding the program to the Binghamton and Oneonta Districts.

column1: On February 3
column3: the Trustees purchased a home located at 1760 North Washington Street in Scranton for $38
column4: 000. A Board of Directors was established for the purpose of managing and operating the proposed Scranton Home. The Scranton home was opened in January of 1959
column5: housing six residents. The Scranton Home remained in operation until 1974
column6: with 10 individuals in residence relocating to the new Hilltop Campus in Johnson City
column8: which opened in March of that year.

column1: A second home was generously donated by Mrs. Delphine Garrett of Philadelphia. The facility was named Murray-Tufts-Garrett Manor in honor of her mother
column2: her grandfather
column3: and her. She also established a significant endowment
column4: which made it possible to build a series of additions to the facility. The new addition was occupied in 1965.";"http://www.unitedmethodisthomes.org/about-us/history/";"https://www.facebook.com/UnitedMH/info";;"http://www.unitedmethodisthomes.org/employment/";"http://www.unitedmethodisthomes.org/contact-admissions/admissions/";;"not mentioned in the website";"not mentioned in the website";"not mentioned in the website";"not mentioned in the website";"not mentioned in the website";"not mentioned in the website";;"http://www.unitedmethodisthomes.org/wp-content/themes/umh-v0.0/images/content/pages/about-us_history.jpg";;;;;

column1: 714260;"KAI'S COMFY CORNER CHILD CARE & LEARNING CTR";"1601 S 9TH ST";"PHILADELPHIA";"PA";19148;"PHILADELPHIA";2152719919;"http://comfycorner.org/";;"Welcome to Kai’s Comfy Corner Child Care and Learning Center. Early childhood years are a very special time in your child’s development. We are excited to become a part of this learning experience.

Kai’s Comfy Corner has been in operation since 2002. We were founded to fulfill an increasing need for quality childcare in our area. We have a diverse group of children and staff. We provide a quality
column2: age appropriate curriculum that fosters a child’s total self
column3: teaching them self-confidence
column4: self-awareness
column6: while embracing and celebrating the differences in us all.

column1: Kai’s Comfy Corner is a state licensed facility and is Keystone Stars accredited. We believe each child is a unique individual and we are sensitive to their social
column2: emotional
column3: physical and cognitive development. Our program focuses on the process of learning and helping children enjoy successful experiences. We encourage not just learning
column4: but “the love of learning”.

column1: At Kai’s Comfy Corner our philosophy is ""Laugh. Play. Learn."" Our center is a place where children are allowed to be children
column2: to explore their world using their imagination
column3: and to feel loved and cared for in a safe and healthy environment.

column1: Our teachers are creative and caring individuals who are dedicated to the children in their care. They are supported with trainings
column2: resources and the freedom to create unique learning experiences for our children. They strive to create a partnership with parents and guardians who we believe are the most significant adults in a child’s life. Their goal is to make sure your child is equipped with the knowledge and social skills needed to have a successful start.

column1: Our Center is enhanced by the latest state of the art security video surveillance and an electronic buzz in security door. We have an onsite gated playground with jungle gym and safety surfacing for daily outdoor play and a parking lot for convenient drop off and pickups.";"http://comfycorner.org/";;"6:30 A.M. – 6:30 P.M.

Monday – Friday";;;;"y";"y";"y";"y";"n";"n";"http://comfycorner.org/images/logo_top.gif";"http://comfycorner.org/gallery/images/2008_graduation_01.jpg";"http://comfycorner.org/gallery/images/linville_orchards_03.jpg";"http://comfycorner.org/gallery/images/linville_orchards_04.jpg";"http://comfycorner.org/gallery/images/teachers_01.jpg";;

column1: At Tiny Treasures
column2: we believe that all children are individuals and should be treated as such. We concentrate on school readiness at age appropriate levels for each child. Each child will work at their own pace to maximize their learning capabilities. We recognize that each child has unique personalities and learning styles. Our teachers are qualified individuals with years of experience and are nurturing to each child. Our teachers are committed to early childhood education at Tiny Treasures therefore you will see the consistent
column3: patient
column4: kind
column8: year after year. We feel consistency with the teachers and children is a vital role in the success of your child's development.

column1: One of our goals that we strive for is to produce a child care facility that becomes a place that the children want to come to on a daily basis; a place where the children feel safe and secure with their teachers. By doing this we collaborate with the families to include them in this early learning experience with their child.  A daily report will be sent to communicate your child's activities throughout the day.  We do assessments on the children in the Fall and Spring. Parent conferences upon request are held to share the goals that they have reached and what we are striving to conquer for next time.  Families are invited throughout the year to many events that we host at our centers.  Our monthly newsletters are sent to inform the families of curriculum
column2: and exciting new events that will occur. 715187;"RED MILL ELEMENTARY SCHOOL-AGE PROGRAM";"700 RED MILL RD";"ETTERS";"PA";17319;"YORK";7177743923;"http://www.wssd.k12.pa.us/red_mill.cfm";"KWagner@wssd.k12.pa.us";"Red Mill Elementary School is located in Etters on approximately 42 acres of ground on which sits the school
column2: a playground
column3: two multi-purpose athletic fields
column4: and plenty of open area. The school is home to approximately 575 students in kindergarten through fifth grade.  Students enjoy the benefit of an average class size of 22.8 students. Most Red Mill teachers possess or are working towards advance degrees in their field.  Red Mill teachers annually participate in staff development academies
column5: which provide opportunities for professional growth and training. Through their participation in these academies
column6: the staff continually improves their skills
column8: and techniques for enhancing teaching and learning thus creating an enhanced learning environment for all students.

column1: Red Mill provides a strong foundation in the basic skills with an integrated language arts approach to reading
column2: writing
column3: spelling
column4: listening
column5: and speaking.  In the primary grades
column6: our Kid Writing and Writing Process approach enables students
column8: to move through the stages of writing development
column10: and to improve their writing ability more rapidly.  Sequential development of number concepts and computation is strengthened with an emphasis on critical thinking skills
column12: and hands-on learning in mathematics.  The curriculum provides opportunities for incorporating both enrichment and accelerated activities to meet individual student needs. Academically
column13: the children at Red Mill achieve at or above expected levels in every area on District-wide assessments and the Pennsylvania System of School Assessment.

column1: Technology skills are taught through an integrated approach in the classroom.  The classroom teachers plan and teach lessons which utilize technology in all grades. This effort is supported by 5 laptop computer carts
column2: digital movie and still cameras
column3: in-focus projectors
column4: iPads
column5: and supervised Internet access.  In addition
column6: most of the kindergarten through fifth grade classrooms are equipped with an interactive white board.  The library contains an up-to-date and extensive collection of children’s literature and reference materials
column9: and each student receives weekly instruction in lifelong literacy skills.

column1: Students at Red Mill have the opportunity to expand their talents and skills through specialized classes in art
column2: music
column3: library
column4: and physical education.  String and band instrument instruction begins in the fourth grade.  All students at Red Mill are able to participate in a variety of activities
column9: and Junior Achievement lessons. After-school clubs and tutoring opportunities are available outside of the school day for selected children.

column1: Parent participation is encouraged and welcomed at Red Mill. In fact
column2: many parents and grandparents volunteer in a variety of ways every day.  The Parent-Teacher Organization (PTO) provides resources for field trips
column3: assemblies
column4: after-school programs
column5: and daily planners for every student.  A group of dedicated and energetic volunteers form the PTO
column6: making a significant contribution to the total school experience for Red Mill’s children.

column3: Snails and Puppy Dog Tails Child Care Center is a full service
column4: licensed Child Care center that offers after school care in Lewisberry Etters
column6: Fishing Creek. We have 20 well trained staff members
column7: five of whom have four-year degrees. We offer full and part time care for babies from 6 weeks old to school age children up to 12 years old
column8: between the hours of 6:30 AM and 6:00 PM
column9: Monday through Friday. We offer a Preschool Program
column10: a Kindergarten Program
column13: a Before-and-After-School Program and a Summer-Program.

column1: We have a baby room with only four babies
column2: unlike many large New Cumberland daycare centers which have as many as 12 to 16 babies in one room. Our Young toddler room has between 10 and 12 children between the ages of 1 and 2 years and has three staff members. Our Older Toddler Room has between 12 and 18 children between the ages of 2 to 3 years and has three to four staff members. Our Center serves Etters
column3: Newberrytown
column4: York Haven
column5: Lewisberry and  Fishing Creek childcare and has three Preschool Rooms. The First two are limited to 10 children each
column6: and are used as a transition between the Toddler Rooms and a more classroom like environment. The final Preschool Room is for children who will be attending Kindergarten the following year and is run like a classroom at school
column7: with a maximum of 24 children. Unlike a classroom at school
column8: our large Preschool Room has Two Teachers with Elementary Education Degrees
column9: one of which has ten years teaching experience and the other has over twenty. These two teachers also have an assistant. In this way
column10: we are able to fully prepare your child for school.

column1: We have a Kindergarten Program with between 12 and 18 children and two staff members. The Kindergarten children have their own building with two separate floors. The first floor is set up as a recreation room area with everything from pool and ping-pong
column2: to air-hockey and skee-ball. The second floor is set up as a classroom environment with two large classrooms and a computer resource area. The entire third floor of this building is our storage for education and craft resources
column3: which all the staff access. We have more in resources in this area than are typically stored at ten of our competitors combined.

column1: We have two full size school buses with which we transport our kindergarteners and school age children to and from school. We also use these buses to go on field trips throughout the year with all our children four years and older. We use our school buses to transport our school age children in our School Age Summer Program on four to five field trips per week (see the list of field trips scheduled for 2012 under the Summer Program tab above). 976715;"TENDER CARE LEARNING CENTER";"600 HOSPITAL WAY";"MCKEESPORT";"PA";15132;"Allegheny";4126647090;"http://www.earlyeducationpros.org/tendercare/locations.jsp";;"Tender Care Learning Centers offers parents something a little different. It is a place where children see just how amazing learning can be; setting a passionate foundation for education that will support them throughout their lives. More than just another Pittsburgh daycare
column2: Tender Care Learning Centers uses a holistic approach to education that shows children how fun it can be to learn. While we do offer Pittsburgh child care services
column3: our approach would not be given due justice with such an overall label.

column1: Tender Care Learning Centers are a member of the larger family that is Bradford Child Care Services. Since 1982
column2: Bradford Child Care Services has been setting the bar in early education
column3: and their approach is supported by the more than 2
column4: 000 families that sign their children up for classes in three states. While a traditional Pittsburgh day care may offer very basic services to the children they enroll
column5: Tender Care Learning Centers provides some important extras that distinguish them from those other Pittsburgh day care centers.

column1: We are not really a day care
column2: but rather a child care center. While this may seem like nothing more than semantics to some
column3: for us there is a major difference. Instead of just keeping your child busy while he or she is in our care
column4: we support their educational and personal growth with proven educational tools.

column1: We offer an environment that feels more like a home than a school. We understand that children learn best when they are comfortable and that they are more comfortable when they feel like they are home.
Our teachers are highly qualified
column2: and our approach makes them more passionate at work. Since we give our instructors the freedom to be creative with the children
column3: they get a higher level of personal satisfaction. The result: a child care center with instructors that have been with us for a decade or more in an industry with a very high turnover rate.

column1: We look at parents as integral in our approach. By involving you in the education of your child as much as possible
column2: we feel that we are further enhancing the ""homey"" feeling of our centers. We are very proud of the relationships that we maintain with our amazing parents
column3: and we often learn a lot from their perspectives.

column1: Our programs are age appropriate
column2: and take into account the different learning paces of all children. We want our children to feel confident and free to create and explore
column3: and this ""open ended"" approach we use helps to encourage that.";"http://www.earlyeducationpros.org/tendercare/locations.jsp";;;"http://www.earlyeducationpros.org/tendercare/careers.jsp";"http://www.earlyeducationpros.org/tendercare/enrollment.jsp";;"y";"y";"y";"y";"y";"y";;;;;;;

977107;"CONEMAUGH VALLEY CHILD CARE";"1451 FRANKSTOWN RD";"JOHNSTOWN";"PA";15902;"CAMBRIA";8145390405;"http://www.cccdc.us/cvalley.php";;"Conemaugh Valley Elementary Child Care is operated by the Cambria County Child Development Corporation which has been serving the children and families of Cambria County for over 40 years. Our quality programs are the result of years of experience caring for children.

The Conemaugh Valley Elementary Child Care program operates Monday through Friday from 5:45AM until school begins and when school ends until 6:15PM and will be open for snow delays and early dismissals. The program is located in the Conemaugh Valley Elementary School for children from pre-school through age 12. This program is operated by caring and experienced staff. The Director holds a Bachelor of Arts degree in Child Development and Family Relations and all staff members are required to take at least 18 hours of continuing education per year.
This program has earned the highly prestigious STAR 3 designation from The Pennsylvania Keystone STARS Quality Rating Program.
Conemaugh Valley Elementary Child Care participates in the Child and Adult Care Food Program and provides children with a nutritious afternoon snack.

The staff of Conemaugh Valley Elementary Child Care continues the Cambria County County Child Development standard of excellence by providing children with both educational and physical programming. For example
column2: this year the children will be learning about their surroundings
column3: both indoors and outdoors
column4: through a variety of hands-on projects. The children are also physically engaged with the SPARK program. The staff of Conemaugh Valley work very hard to keep the children involved in activities with a child focused curriculum.

column1: Aside from your child’s classroom
column2: we have two additional rooms: The Science Center and Imagination room.

column1: The Science Center:

The Science Center is located across from the Pre-K classroom. Your child’s class will spend 30 minutes a day in this room. Here our teachers will focus on science lessons and experiments. Resources included in this room are: a light table with x-rays and color blocks

column1: The Imagination Room:
The Imagination Room is located in the middle of the building
column2: across from the office. Each room will spend at least 30 minutes a day in this room.  Here your child will participate in dramatic play and gross motor activities. Resources this room includes: a puppet stage with puppets
column3: a play kitchen
column4: dress up

column1: In the Classroom:
Every month you will receive a calendar
column2: which follows a curriculum

column1: 1093858;"GRANDVIEW MONTESSORI";"131 BIGHAM ST";"PITTSBURGH";"PA";15211;"ALLEGHENY";4129043066;"http://www.grandviewmontessori.org/";"info@grandviewmontessori.org

;Thank you so much for showing an interest in having your child attend Grandview Montessori.  It is with great pleasure that we inform you about our program and what we have to offer your child.  We believe our program and approach will prepare students for their primary school years and provide them with the necessary tools to become life-long learners.

Montessori education focuses on learning through concrete manipulation of objects and materials in a prepared learning environment.  Students are able to select works in the classroom that pique their interest and either choose to work on it independently or in collaboration with another child.
The Reggio approach that we utilize in the afternoon portion of the day focuses on group projects and collective learning with all subject areas being integrated.
The Montessori and Reggio pedagogies stem from the same philosophies of learning and blend extremely well together
column2: stressing the student as the builder of knowledge and the teacher as a facilitator.  They are both designed to provide opportunities for each child to grow and experience social awareness
column3: emotional well-being
column4: physical development

column1: 1093919;"EDUCATIONWORKS AT HAMILTON DISSTON SCHOOL";"6801 COTTAGE ST";"PHILADELPHIA";"PA";19135;"PHILADELPHIA";2152196115;"http://webgui.phila.k12.pa.us/offices/e/earlychild";;"The mission of the Office of Early Childhood Education is to provide high quality

column5: and arrives at school ready to learn and succeed. Our guiding principles are systemic in approach
column7: and are characterized by significant levels of parent involvement and community support. The Office of Early Childhood Education looks forward to the time when all Philadelphia children from birth to age six and their families receive the health
column9: and social services and support needed for healthy development and educational success. The scope of this vision requires the Office of Early Childhood Education to increase and maintain its authentic

column14: and parents. As we work together rather than separately

column20: developmentally appropriate programs and services to all of Philadelphia’s young children and their families.";"http://webgui.phila.k12.pa.us/offices/e/earlychild";;;;"http://webgui.phila.k12.pa.us/offices/e/earlychild/proposed-policies--procedures-structure/enrollment";;"n";"n";"y";"y";"n";"n";;"http://webgui.phila.k12.pa.us/uploads/_M/_e/_M_exrV0MbNddc0qxsEIPg/FAST.png";;;;;

1094071;"ITHAN MONTESSORI SCHOOL";"536 CONESTOGA RD";"VILLANOVA";"PA";19085;"DELAWARE";6109374499;"https://www.ithanmontessori.com/contact.php";"info@ithanmontessori.com";"Developing and nurturing your child’s love of learning is a responsibility we take very seriously. Our goal is to provide an educational atmosphere that incorporates the Montessori Philosophy emphasizing development of your child’s body
column2: mind and spirit. After years of careful observation and working with children
column3: Dr. Maria Montessori (1870-1952) developed her philosophy that the child absorbs learning through experience. Montessori children learn through a process of discovery and given the proper environment their natural love of learning flourishes.  Teachers at Ithan Montessori strive to create a unique learning environment where children are encouraged to respect themselves
column4: others and the environment.

column1: Our classrooms provide a prepared environment where children are free to respond to their natural tendency to work.  Each child is free to choose to work alone or with another child. Working with a friend encourages cooperation and harmony.  If a child chooses to work alone
column2: he or she learns to respect the other students in the classroom and knows not to disturb one another.  When a child finishes with his or her work
column3: he or she returns each item to its appropriate place.

column1: The children's innate passion for learning is encouraged by giving them opportunities to engage in spontaneous
column2: purposeful activities with the guidance of a trained adult.  This approach allows the child to develop self-confidence
column3: inner discipline and motivation.  The Montessori classroom and activities are child-directed
column4: non-competitive and self-correcting.  As a result
column5: each child experiences success rather than frustration
column6: which in turn develops his or her sense of self-esteem and self-confidence and allows him or her to be self-motivated. Infant Room- A caregiver in our infant room is responsible for caring for the infants. The children in this room may range from 6 weeks old to 1 year old. The caregiver is required to feed infants
column2: change their diapers
column3: and interact with the infants in a positive manner. Caregiver must be able to sit on the floor and interact with the infants.

column1: Toddler Room- A caregiver in our toddler room is responsible for planning daily activities for the toddlers in our program. In addition to daily activities they are also responsible for feeding the toddlers and changing their diapers as well as potty training. Children in our toddler room may range from 1 years old to 3 years old.

Preschool Room- A caregiver in our preschool room will be required to plan daily activities in order to prepare the children for a school environment. In addition to planning activities this individual will be responsible for serving the children lunch as well as interacting with them in a positive manner. Children in this room may range from 3 years old to 5 years old.

School Age Program- A caregiver in this room is responsible for getting the children on and off the school bus safely. A care giver in this room is also responsible for helping the children complete homework and study. column2: creative and loving environment for every child. We want your child to feel comfortable and have the opportunity to learn and experience new things.We understand that each child has different learning styles
column3: and it is our goal to provide your child with a learning style that works best for him/her.  We practice age appropriate techniques as well as positive reinforcement
column4: and redirection.

column1: Our staff are trained to respect and care for your child in a compassionate
column2: understanding and warm fashion. We undergo a thorough screening process to ensure your child is receiving the best possible care including:

column1: ​ 1. Child Care Education/Training
2. First aide and CPR Certification
3. Criminal Background Checks
4. Child Abuse Clearances
5. FBI Fingerprinting
6. Magistrate Docket Checks
7. Megan's Law Background Checks
8. Drug Testing
